WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.290
Okay, here we go.

00:00:04.510 --> 00:00:10.380
I had the good fortune, which is maybe apparent by the

00:00:10.380 --> 00:00:14.710
gray beard, to be around almost 30 years ago and was

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:18.640
invited by Tim O'Reilly to the first kind of

00:00:18.640 --> 00:00:23.170
gathering of people where he wanted to gather momentum behind this term

00:00:23.170 --> 00:00:28.010
called open source as something of its own meaning and definition.

00:00:28.010 --> 00:00:32.610
And the first open source conferences, I fell in love with

00:00:32.700 --> 00:00:35.380
protocols and built Jabber XMPP back in the 90

00:00:35.380 --> 00:00:37.560
s, again, almost 30 years ago.

00:00:37.590 --> 00:00:39.160
Thank you.

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:43.320
And so I've seen this whole arc of open source from

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:47.710
the very beginning and how it's changed over the years and

00:00:47.710 --> 00:00:51.260
really what it's become with the kind of GitHub architecture where

00:00:51.490 --> 00:00:52.300
we're at today.

00:00:52.440 --> 00:00:55.230
And we're facing something new now.

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:58.900
And I've been telling people code is tap water.

00:00:58.900 --> 00:01:00.940
It is that available.

00:01:00.940 --> 00:01:02.250
It is that common.

00:01:02.250 --> 00:01:04.850
Everyone's going to have access to it.

00:01:04.890 --> 00:01:08.410
So I am putting forth an idea that I had last fall

00:01:08.410 --> 00:01:12.080
, that the future of open source is social.

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:14.940
And of course, it's built on Proto.

00:01:14.940 --> 00:01:20.190
Today, when you look at most open source activity, it

00:01:20.190 --> 00:01:21.970
is forks and clones.

00:01:22.090 --> 00:01:24.400
It goes through PRs and there's issues.

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:25.710
It all goes to upstream.

00:01:25.830 --> 00:01:28.240
There's maintainer, a group of maintainers.

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:32.470
And while the ESR is original cathedral and bazaar

00:01:32.470 --> 00:01:35.260
, right, there's a lot of, you know,

00:01:35.260 --> 00:01:39.500
this looks like a cathedral again, even though there's just

00:01:39.500 --> 00:01:40.920
a lot of little cathedrals.

00:01:40.940 --> 00:01:45.430
And I believe that we can actually build on at Proto

00:01:45.430 --> 00:01:48.970
something that is a true bazaar, where the features

00:01:48.970 --> 00:01:53.540
and capabilities that people are developing and creating are moving between each

00:01:53.550 --> 00:01:54.630
other peer to peer.

00:01:54.630 --> 00:01:58.200
No gatekeepers, no upstream, no waiting for releases or

00:01:58.370 --> 00:01:58.900
merging.

00:01:58.940 --> 00:02:01.600
You just have capabilities that flow.

00:02:01.600 --> 00:02:03.820
Every repo becomes alive.

00:02:03.820 --> 00:02:05.800
Every copy of the repo becomes alive.

00:02:05.800 --> 00:02:07.250
And there's no upstream.

00:02:07.300 --> 00:02:08.280
It's all sideways.

00:02:08.280 --> 00:02:14.780
Today, when you think about software development, people have features

00:02:14.780 --> 00:02:15.750
they want created.

00:02:15.870 --> 00:02:19.610
It often goes to like an architect or designer or, you

00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:24.170
know, a developer who's planning those features and creates maybe

00:02:24.170 --> 00:02:27.370
a requirements document or a scope of what they're going to

00:02:27.370 --> 00:02:28.120
implement.

00:02:28.150 --> 00:02:30.830
And then it goes into a developer who's actually like doing

00:02:30.830 --> 00:02:33.320
the engineering and the code and they output code.

00:02:33.340 --> 00:02:35.520
And it gets distributed using Git.

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:40.540
So I thought, what if we've got these coding agents

00:02:40.630 --> 00:02:43.550
that make everything different?

00:02:43.550 --> 00:02:48.160
What if when people now are using coding agents directly, they

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:50.460
don't have to be developers anymore.

00:02:50.460 --> 00:02:53.570
They create a new feature or capability on top of an open

00:02:53.570 --> 00:02:54.820
source project.

00:02:54.820 --> 00:02:58.620
They can just tell the coding agent, package up and describe

00:02:58.620 --> 00:03:01.700
this feature, how you implemented it, not the code,

00:03:01.700 --> 00:03:03.480
the description of the feature.

00:03:03.490 --> 00:03:07.050
This capability, that is what we share.

00:03:07.060 --> 00:03:10.120
That is the new form of open source peer-to-

00:03:10.120 --> 00:03:10.980
peer sharing.

00:03:10.980 --> 00:03:14.740
And that is what I called VIT, short for vital

00:03:14.740 --> 00:03:17.980
ity, thinking that every code can be alive and be vital

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:19.060
, every repo.

00:03:19.060 --> 00:03:24.390
And so now any open source or any open source project with

00:03:24.390 --> 00:03:27.240
a coding agent can take a description of a capability or a

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:30.140
feature and it can implement it for that person.

00:03:30.140 --> 00:03:32.640
You never need to pull a release or an upstream again.

00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:37.420
It becomes yours and it lives in your features and capabilities coming

00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:38.550
from other people.

00:03:40.140 --> 00:03:44.210
So the things that you can share socially, you can capture

00:03:44.210 --> 00:03:45.780
up skills, right?

00:03:45.780 --> 00:03:48.340
Today, you can take those skills and share them and just

00:03:48.340 --> 00:03:48.920
post them.

00:03:48.920 --> 00:03:51.540
And they can come from your network, the people that you

00:03:51.540 --> 00:03:52.200
follow.

00:03:52.200 --> 00:03:56.710
And more importantly, you can take the capabilities, these structured

00:03:56.780 --> 00:04:01.340
change instructions, these improvements, and the people that you trust

00:04:01.350 --> 00:04:05.050
can actually publish these and you can go follow them and then

00:04:05.050 --> 00:04:06.640
you can post and share things back.

00:04:06.640 --> 00:04:11.830
The capabilities are what really grow a code base to adapt to

00:04:11.830 --> 00:04:13.930
your, what things that you want.

00:04:13.930 --> 00:04:17.320
And both, and the skills teach agents new things and they

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:19.760
both flow through the same trust network.

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:22.640
It is a human and agent collaboration process.

00:04:22.640 --> 00:04:25.610
As a human, you're still logging into Blue Sky.

00:04:25.610 --> 00:04:28.100
You still have to vet that to make sure that this is

00:04:28.150 --> 00:04:30.340
something safe for it to implement.

00:04:30.340 --> 00:04:32.930
And you, if you believe in it and you've used

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:35.060
it, you can vouch for it too, right?

00:04:35.060 --> 00:04:38.230
And those signals go into the network very similar to likes and

00:04:38.460 --> 00:04:39.680
reposts.

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:44.330
Your agent actually does the work to skim the network,

00:04:44.330 --> 00:04:48.970
to look at what is available and maybe look at what capabilities

00:04:48.970 --> 00:04:52.400
it thinks you might like and present to you things that it

00:04:52.400 --> 00:04:53.880
could implement on your behalf.

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:57.100
It can, you can tell it to remix those into your

00:04:57.100 --> 00:04:57.780
code base.

00:04:57.790 --> 00:05:00.300
Then you can package it up and say, ship this new

00:05:00.300 --> 00:05:02.300
thing that I did back into the network.

00:05:02.300 --> 00:05:05.180
And other agents out there using that will be able to see

00:05:05.300 --> 00:05:06.560
those capabilities.

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:09.260
And you can tell it to learn a new skill, like

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:11.720
go look for other people that I'm following and skills that

00:05:11.720 --> 00:05:14.450
they've published and go learn that skill.

00:05:14.450 --> 00:05:16.430
It's all built on AppRoto.

00:05:16.430 --> 00:05:20.080
These are just lexicons that live in your PDS

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:21.120
with posts.

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:22.790
It is your trust graph.

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:27.200
It is your agents that work the network on your behalf and

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:30.370
everybody can build, share, build, share, build,

00:05:30.370 --> 00:05:31.020
share.

00:05:31.020 --> 00:05:32.750
That is VIT.

00:05:32.750 --> 00:05:36.780
And it is as easy to get started as NPM install

00:05:36.780 --> 00:05:37.290
VIT.

00:05:37.290 --> 00:05:40.590
And you can VIT login and you can go initialize

00:05:40.630 --> 00:05:44.230
any open source project to use VIT and use your coding

00:05:44.230 --> 00:05:44.660
agent.

00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:46.300
It will know how to do everything.

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:50.430
It comes with a skill and we can make the world of

00:05:50.430 --> 00:05:52.600
open source social in the future.

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:54.360
That's it.

00:05:54.360 --> 00:05:58.960
So there's a whole
